JavaStream introduced in java8 to process collections in functional style (lambda)
JavaStream used for filtering,mapping and reducing data
JavaStream Works with collection objects as map,list,set

Functional interface
contains exactly one abstract method and used for lambda expressions

Java Functional Interfaces (Simple Comparison)

Interface	        Takes (Input)	   Returns (Output)	     What It Does    	Example

Predicate<T>        One value	       boolean     	        Checks a condition	 Is age > 18?
Function<T,R>	    One value	       New value	        Changes data	     Name → Length
Consumer<T>	        One value	       Nothing	            Uses data	         Print name
Supplier<T>	        Nothing	           One value            Gives data	         Random number


✅ Java Stream Operations Table

Stream Operation	Functional Interface	What It Does

Java Stream Operations Table (Complete)
Operation	Functional Interface	What It Does
filter()	Predicate<T>	Filters elements by condition
map()	Function<T, R>	Transforms elements
forEach()	Consumer<T>	Performs action on elements
sorted()	Comparator<T>	Sorts elements
distinct()	—	Removes duplicate elements
limit()	—	Limits number of elements
skip()	—	Skips elements
count()	—	Counts elements
anyMatch()	Predicate<T>	Checks if any element matches
allMatch()	Predicate<T>	Checks if all elements match
noneMatch()	Predicate<T>	Checks if no element matches
findFirst()	—	Gets first element
findAny()	—	Gets any element
collect()	Collector	Converts stream to collection
reduce()	BinaryOperator<T>	Combines elements
groupingBy()	Function<T, K>	Groups elements
partitioningBy()	Predicate<T>	Splits into two groups (true / false)
flatMap()	Function<T, Stream<R>>	Flattens nested streams
mapToInt()	ToIntFunction<T>	Converts to IntStream
mapToDouble()	ToDoubleFunction<T>	Converts to DoubleStream
average()	—	Calculates average
max()	Comparator<T>	Finds maximum
min()	Comparator<T>	Finds minimum
